</P>
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Whoopi Goldberg doesn't see moving from the stage and screen to a situation 
comedy as a step down. 
</P>
<P>
"As a girl from the projects, I'm not at all disappointed in the way things are 
going. 
</P>
<P>
This is what I've always dreamed about. And I'm still here, which is the 
phenomenal thing," the comedian says in the April 9 issue of People magazine. 
</P>
<P>
Goldberg, who went from an acclaimed one-woman Broadway show to the lead in 
Steven Spielberg's movie "The Color Purple," stars with Jean Stapleton in 
"Bagdad Cafe" on CBS. 
</P>
<P>
"One thing I'm not is a flash in the pan," Goldberg said. "I have not done 
anything I'm ashamed of. Things haven't always turned out the way I wanted, but 
I did the best job I could. They (the critics) built Whoopi's image. I didn't." 
</P>
